AB  - Identifying with one's ethnic group can contribute to the well-being of racial/ethnic minorities; however, little research has investigated the mechanisms that account for this relationship. Using a sample of South Asian Canadians, we examined whether this relationship can be explained in part by appraisals of intergroup coping options-beliefs about how one's ingroup as a whole can respond effectively to discrimination. Participants appraised the availability of 2 individual coping options and 2 intergroup coping options. The 2 individual coping options included appraisals about personally being able to avoid potential instances of discrimination (proactive avoidance), as well as being able to successfully regulate the negative emotions stemming from perceived discrimination (emotion regulation). The 2 intergroup coping options included appraisals about one's ethnic group working together to better their status (collective action) as well as ingroup members being able to effectively deal with negative societal beliefs about their group (social creativity). Participants who highly identified with their ethnic group reported greater satisfaction with their lives. Of the 4 coping options, collective action and social creativity were simple mediators of the relationship between ethnic identification and life satisfaction. Collective action emerged as the lone unique mediator when using the more robust test of multiple mediation. The results provide further evidence that group identification promotes well-being for racial/ethnic minorities, in part, because it encourages beliefs about one's group effectively responding to discrimination.
